IMPORTANT IMPLEMENTATION NOTES
	1.	WVC requires Linux for production. Mac will crash with headless experimental API.
Add a compatibility mode fallback for local dev on Mac using WVC’s browserHeadless: false
with a visible Chrome window.
	2.	SVG stroke-dasharray animations: the –len CSS variable must equal the
actual SVG path length. Claude cannot know exact path lengths, so generate
a <script> block at the bottom of each SVG that auto-calculates and sets
–len on all .stroke elements using getTotalLength():

document.querySelectorAll('.stroke').forEach(el => {
  if (el.getTotalLength) {
    el.style.setProperty('--len', el.getTotalLength());
  }
});


	2.	Include this script in every scene HTML file, runs on load.

const t = parseFloat(new URLSearchParams(location.search).get('t') || '0');
// Then delay all animations by -t (use negative animation-delay)


	8.	Thumbnail generation: after iframe loads a scene, call html2canvas on the
iframe’s contentDocument.body. Do this 500ms after load to let animations settle.
	9.	The Claude streaming response will be raw SVG markup. Parse it on the fly:
buffer tokens until you have a complete opening <svg tag, then inject into
the DOM and keep updating innerHTML as more tokens arrive.
	10.	Transitions in FFmpeg xfade: the offset param is the timestamp (in seconds
from video start) at which the transition begins. Calculate as:
offset = sum of all previous scene durations - transition_duration/2
Chain: [0][1]xfade=fade:duration=0.5:offset=7.75[v01];[v01][2]xfade=fade:duration=0.5:offset=15.25[v012]

